# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aerobic-organism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be interconverted to adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP contains one more phosphate group than ADP, while AMP contains one fewer phosphate group.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Energy transfer used by all living things is a result of dephosphorylation of ATP by enzymes known as ATPases.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The cleavage of a phosphate group from ATP results in the coupling of energy to metabolic reactions and a by-product of ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ATP is continually reformed from lower-energy species ADP and AMP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The biosynthesis of ATP is achieved throughout processes such as substrate-level phosphorylation, oxidative phosphorylation, and photophosphorylation, all of which facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP cycling supplies the energy needed to do work in a biological system, the thermodynamic process of transferring energy from one source to another.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] There are two types of energy: potential energy and kinetic energy.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Potential energy can be thought of as stored energy, or usable energy that is available to do work.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Kinetic energy is the energy of an object as a result of its motion.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The significance of ATP is in its ability to store potential energy within the phosphate bonds.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy stored between these bonds can then be transferred to do work.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] For example, the transfer of energy from ATP to the protein myosin causes a conformational change when connecting to actin during muscle contraction.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] It takes multiple reactions between myosin and actin to effectively produce one muscle contraction, and, therefore, the availability of large amounts of ATP is required to produce each muscle contraction.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] For this reason, biological processes have evolved to produce efficient ways to replenish the potential energy of ATP from ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Breaking one of ATP's phosphorus bonds generates approximately 30.5 kilojoules per mole of ATP (7.3 kcal).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP can be converted, or powered back to ATP through the process of releasing the chemical energy available in food; in humans, this is constantly performed via aerobic respiration in the mitochondria.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Plants use photosynthetic pathways to convert and store energy from sunlight, also conversion of ADP to ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Animals use the energy released in the breakdown of glucose and other molecules to convert ADP to ATP, which can then be used to fuel necessary growth and cell maintenance.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The ten-step catabolic pathway of glycolysis is the initial phase of free-energy release in the breakdown of glucose and can be split into two phases, the preparatory phase and payoff phase.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP and phosphate are needed as precursors to synthesize ATP in the payoff reactions of the TCA cycle and oxidative phosphorylation mechanism.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] During the payoff phase of glycolysis, the enzymes phosphoglycerate kinase and pyruvate kinase facilitate the addition of a phosphate group to ADP by way of substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Glycolysis is performed by all living organisms and consists of 10 steps.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 require the input of energy derived from the hydrolysis of ATP to ADP and Pi (inorganic phosphate), whereas steps 7 and 10 require the input of ADP, each yielding ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The enzymes necessary to break down glucose are found in the cytoplasm, the viscous fluid that fills living cells, where the glycolytic reactions take place.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The citric acid cycle, also known as the Krebs cycle or the TCA (tricarboxylic acid) cycle is an 8-step process that takes the pyruvate generated by glycolysis and generates 4 NADH, FADH2, and GTP, which is further converted to ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] It is only in step 5, where GTP is generated, by succinyl-CoA synthetase, and then converted to ATP, that ADP is used (GTP + ADP → GDP + ATP).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Oxidative phosphorylation produces 26 of the 30 equivalents of ATP generated in cellular respiration by transferring electrons from NADH or FADH2 to O2 through electron carriers.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy released when electrons are passed from higher-energy NADH or FADH2 to the lower-energy O2 is required to phosphorylate ADP and once again generate ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] It is this energy coupling and phosphorylation of ADP to ATP that gives the electron transport chain the name oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] During the initial phases of glycolysis and the TCA cycle, cofactors such as NAD+ donate and accept electrons that aid in the electron transport chain's ability to produce a proton gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The ATP synthase complex exists within the mitochondrial membrane (FO portion) and protrudes into the matrix (F1 portion).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] The energy derived as a result of the chemical gradient is then used to synthesize ATP by coupling the reaction of inorganic phosphate to ADP in the active site of the ATP synthase enzyme; the equation for this can be written as ADP + Pi → ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] Under normal conditions, small disk-shape platelets circulate in the blood freely and without interaction with one another.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP is stored in dense bodies inside blood platelets and is released upon platelet activation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP interacts with a family of ADP receptors found on platelets (P2Y1, P2Y12, and P2X1), which leads to platelet activation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-diphosphate] ADP in the blood is converted to adenosine by the action of ecto-ADPases, inhibiting further platelet activation via adenosine receptors.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:aerobic-organism/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Aerobic digestion is typically used in an activated sludge treatment plant.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Waste activated sludge and primary sludge are combined, where appropriate, and passed to a thickener where the solids content is increased.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] This substantially reduces the volume that is required to be treated in the digester.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] The process is usually run as a batch process with more than one digester tank in operation at any one time.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Air is pumped through the tank and the contents are stirred to keep the contents fully mixed.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Carbon dioxide, waste air and small quantities of other gases including hydrogen sulfide are given off.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] These waste gases require treatment to reduce odours in works close to housing or capable of generating public nuisance.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] The digestion is continued until the percentage of degradable solids is reduced to between 20% and 10% depending on local conditions.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Where non-sewage waste is being processed, organic waste such as food, cardboard and horticultural waste can be significantly reduced in volume leaving an output that can be used as soil improver or biomass fuel.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Aerobic digestion occurs much faster than anaerobic digestion.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] The process is usually run at ambient temperature and the process is much less complex and easier to manage than anaerobic digestion.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] The operating costs are typically much greater for aerobic digestion than for anaerobic digestion because of energy used by the blowers, pumps and motors needed to add oxygen to the process.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] However, recent technological advances include non-electrically aerated filter systems that use natural air currents for the aeration instead of electrically operated machinery.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] The digested sludge is relatively low in residual energy and although it can be dried and incinerated to produce heat, the energy yield is very much lower than that produced by anaerobic digestion.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] Autothermal thermophilic aerobic digestion is a faecal sludge treatment design concept that uses the nutrients in the sludge and the metabolic heat of the bacteria to create high temperatures in the aerobic digester.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] This gradually shifts the microbial community towards thermophilic at temperatures typically at 55-degree Celsius or above.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-digestion] While the higher aeration requirements of autothermal thermophilic aerobic digestion further increases energy use and potential smell nuisance, the increased temperature makes the resulting biosolids much safer for re-use.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] If the electron acceptor is oxygen, the process is more specifically known as aerobic cellular respiration.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] If the electron acceptor is a molecule other than oxygen, this is anaerobic cellular respiration – not to be confused with fermentation, which is also an anaerobic process, but it is not respiration, as no external electron acceptor is involved.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The reactions involved in respiration are catabolic reactions, which break large molecules into smaller ones, producing ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Respiration is one of the key ways a cell releases chemical energy to fuel cellular activity.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The overall reaction occurs in a series of biochemical steps, some of which are redox reactions.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Although cellular respiration is technically a combustion reaction, it is an unusual one because of the slow, controlled release of energy from the series of reactions.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Nutrients that are commonly used by animal and plant cells in respiration include sugar, amino acids and fatty acids, and the most common oxidizing agent is molecular oxygen (O2).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The negative ΔG indicates that the reaction is exothermic (exergonic) and can occur spontaneously.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The potential of NADH and FADH2 is converted to more ATP through an electron transport chain with oxygen and protons (hydrogen ions) as the "terminal electron acceptors".
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Most of the ATP produced by aerobic cellular respiration is made by oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The energy released is used to create a chemiosmotic potential by pumping protons across a membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This potential is then used to drive ATP synthase and produce ATP from ADP and a phosphate group.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Biology textbooks often state that 38 ATP molecules can be made per oxidized glucose molecule during cellular respiration (2 from glycolysis, 2 from the Krebs cycle, and about 34 from the electron transport system).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] However, this maximum yield is never quite reached because of losses due to leaky membranes as well as the cost of moving pyruvate and ADP into the mitochondrial matrix, and current estimates range around 29 to 30 ATP per glucose.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Aerobic metabolism is up to 15 times more efficient than anaerobic metabolism (which yields 2 molecules of ATP per 1 molecule of glucose).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] However, some anaerobic organisms, such as methanogens are able to continue with anaerobic respiration, yielding more ATP by using inorganic molecules other than oxygen as final electron acceptors in the electron transport chain.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] They share the initial pathway of glycolysis but aerobic metabolism continues with the Krebs cycle and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The post-glycolytic reactions take place in the mitochondria in eukaryotic cells, and in the cytoplasm in prokaryotic cells.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Although plants are net consumers of carbon dioxide and producers of oxygen via photosynthesis, plant respiration accounts for about half of the CO2 generated annually by terrestrial ecosystems.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Glycolysis is a metabolic pathway that takes place in the cytosol of cells in all living organisms.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Glycolysis can be literally translated as "sugar splitting", and occurs regardless of oxygen's presence or absence.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The process converts one molecule of glucose into two molecules of pyruvate (pyruvic acid), generating energy in the form of two net molecules of ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Four molecules of ATP per glucose are actually produced, but two are consumed as part of the preparatory phase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The initial phosphorylation of glucose is required to increase the reactivity (decrease its stability) in order for the molecule to be cleaved into two pyruvate molecules by the enzyme aldolase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] During the pay-off phase of glycolysis, four phosphate groups are transferred to four ADP by substrate-level phosphorylation to make four ATP, and two NADH are also produced during the pay-off phase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Starting with glucose, 1 ATP is used to donate a phosphate to glucose to produce glucose 6-phosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Glycogen can be converted into glucose 6-phosphate as well with the help of glycogen phosphorylase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] During energy metabolism, glucose 6-phosphate becomes fructose 6-phosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] An additional ATP is used to phosphorylate fructose 6-phosphate into fructose 1,6-bisphosphate by the help of phosphofructokinase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Fructose 1,6-biphosphate then splits into two phosphorylated molecules with three carbon chains which later degrades into pyruvate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Pyruvate is oxidized to acetyl-CoA and CO2 by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex (PDC).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The PDC contains multiple copies of three enzymes and is located in the mitochondria of eukaryotic cells and in the cytosol of prokaryotes.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In the conversion of pyruvate to acetyl-CoA, one molecule of NADH and one molecule of CO2 is formed.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The citric acid cycle is also called the *Krebs cycle* or the *tricarboxylic acid cycle*.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] When oxygen is present, acetyl-CoA is produced from the pyruvate molecules created from glycolysis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Once acetyl-CoA is formed, aerobic or anaerobic respiration can occur.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] When oxygen is present, the mitochondria will undergo aerobic respiration which leads to the Krebs cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] However, if oxygen is not present, fermentation of the pyruvate molecule will occur.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In the presence of oxygen, when acetyl-CoA is produced, the molecule then enters the citric acid cycle (Krebs cycle) inside the mitochondrial matrix, and is oxidized to CO2 while at the same time reducing NAD to NADH.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] NADH can be used by the electron transport chain to create further ATP as part of oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] To fully oxidize the equivalent of one glucose molecule, two acetyl-CoA must be metabolized by the Krebs cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Two low-energy waste products, H2O and CO2, are created during this cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The citric acid cycle is an 8-step process involving 18 different enzymes and co-enzymes.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] During the cycle, acetyl-CoA (2 carbons) + oxaloacetate (4 carbons) yields citrate (6 carbons), which is rearranged to a more reactive form called isocitrate (6 carbons).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Isocitrate is modified to become α-ketoglutarate (5 carbons), succinyl-CoA, succinate, fumarate, malate and, finally, oxaloacetate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The net gain from one cycle is 3 NADH and 1 FADH2 as hydrogen (proton plus electron) carrying compounds and 1 high-energy GTP, which may subsequently be used to produce ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Thus, the total yield from 1 glucose molecule (2 pyruvate molecules) is 6 NADH, 2 FADH2, and 2 ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In eukaryotes, oxidative phosphorylation occurs in the mitochondrial cristae.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] It comprises the electron transport chain that establishes a proton gradient (chemiosmotic potential) across the boundary of the inner membrane by oxidizing the NADH produced from the Krebs cycle.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] ATP is synthesized by the ATP synthase enzyme when the chemiosmotic gradient is used to drive the phosphorylation of ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The electrons are finally transferred to exogenous oxygen and, with the addition of two protons, water is formed.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The table below describes the reactions involved when one glucose molecule is fully oxidized into carbon dioxide.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] It is assumed that all the reduced coenzymes are oxidized by the electron transport chain and used for oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Although there is a theoretical yield of 38 ATP molecules per glucose during cellular respiration, such conditions are generally not realized because of losses such as the cost of moving pyruvate (from glycolysis), phosphate, and ADP (substrates for ATP synthesis) into the mitochondria.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] All are actively transported using carriers that utilize the stored energy in the proton electrochemical gradient.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The outcome of these transport processes using the proton electrochemical gradient is that more than 3 H+ are needed to make 1 ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Obviously, this reduces the theoretical efficiency of the whole process and the likely maximum is closer to 28–30 ATP molecules.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In practice the efficiency may be even lower because the inner membrane of the mitochondria is slightly leaky to protons.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Other factors may also dissipate the proton gradient creating an apparently leaky mitochondria.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] An uncoupling protein known as thermogenin is expressed in some cell types and is a channel that can transport protons.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] When this protein is active in the inner membrane it short circuits the coupling between the electron transport chain and ATP synthesis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The potential energy from the proton gradient is not used to make ATP but generates heat.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This is particularly important in brown fat thermogenesis of newborn and hibernating mammals.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] ATP synthase is a key enzyme in cellular respiration that produces ATP using the proton gradient in mitochondria.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] If temperature deviates too far from the optimal range, enzyme activity decreases, reducing ATP production.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This limits the ability of effectors such as muscles and glands to function, threatening homeostasis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] These figures may still require further tweaking as new structural details become available.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The above value of 3 H+ / ATP for the synthase assumes that the synthase translocates 9 protons, and produces 3 ATP, per rotation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The number of protons depends on the number of c subunits in the Fo c-ring, and it is now known that this is 10 in yeast Fo and 8 for vertebrates.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Including one H+ for the transport reactions, this means that synthesis of one ATP requires 1 + 10/3 = 4.33 protons in yeast and 1 + 8/3 = 3.67 in vertebrates.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This would imply that in human mitochondria the 10 protons from oxidizing NADH would produce 2.72 ATP (instead of 2.5) and the 6 protons from oxidizing succinate or ubiquinol would produce 1.64 ATP (instead of 1.5).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This is consistent with experimental results within the margin of error described in a recent review.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The total ATP yield in ethanol or lactic acid fermentation is only 2 molecules coming from glycolysis, because pyruvate is not transferred to the mitochondrion and finally oxidized to the carbon dioxide (CO2), but reduced to ethanol or lactic acid in the cytoplasm.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Without oxygen, pyruvate (pyruvic acid) is not metabolized by cellular respiration but undergoes a process of fermentation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The pyruvate is not transported into the mitochondrion but remains in the cytoplasm, where it is converted to waste products that may be removed from the cell.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This serves the purpose of oxidizing the electron carriers so that they can perform glycolysis again and removing the excess pyruvate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Fermentation oxidizes NADH to NAD+ so it can be re-used in glycolysis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In the absence of oxygen, fermentation prevents the buildup of NADH in the cytoplasm and provides NAD+ for glycolysis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This waste product varies depending on the organism.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In skeletal muscles, the waste product is lactic acid.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This type of fermentation is called lactic acid fermentation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In strenuous exercise, when energy demands exceed energy supply, the respiratory chain cannot process all of the hydrogen atoms joined by NADH.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] During anaerobic glycolysis, NAD+ regenerates when pairs of hydrogen combine with pyruvate to form lactate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Lactate formation is catalyzed by lactate dehydrogenase in a reversible reaction.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Lactate can also be used as an indirect precursor for liver glycogen.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] During recovery, when oxygen becomes available, NAD+ attaches to hydrogen from lactate to form ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In yeast, the waste products are ethanol and carbon dioxide.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] This type of fermentation is known as alcoholic or ethanol fermentation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] The ATP generated in this process is made by substrate-level phosphorylation, which does not require oxygen.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Fermentation is less efficient at using the energy from glucose: only 2 ATP are produced per glucose, compared to the 38 ATP per glucose nominally produced by aerobic respiration.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] Glycolytic ATP, however, is produced more quickly.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] For prokaryotes to continue a rapid growth rate when they are shifted from an aerobic environment to an anaerobic environment, they must increase the rate of the glycolytic reactions.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] In July 2019, a scientific study of Kidd Mine in Canada discovered sulfur-breathing organisms which live 7900 feet (2400 meters) below the surface.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-metabolism] These organisms are also remarkable because they consume minerals such as pyrite as their food source.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] An **aerobic organism** or **aerobe** is an organism that can survive and grow in an oxygenated environment.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] The ability to exhibit aerobic respiration may yield benefits to the aerobic organism, as aerobic respiration yields more energy than anaerobic respiration.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Energy production of the cell involves the synthesis of ATP by an enzyme called ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] In aerobic respiration, ATP synthase is coupled with an electron transport chain in which oxygen acts as a terminal electron acceptor.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] When an organism is able to survive in both oxygen and anaerobic environments, the use of the Pasteur effect can distinguish between facultative anaerobes and aerotolerant organisms.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] If the organism is using fermentation in an anaerobic environment, the addition of oxygen will cause facultative anaerobes to suspend fermentation and begin using oxygen for respiration.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Aerotolerant organisms must continue fermentation in the presence of oxygen.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Facultative organisms grow in both oxygen rich media and oxygen free media.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Aerobic organisms use a process called aerobic respiration to create ATP from ADP and a phosphate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] This equation is a summary of what happens in three series of biochemical reactions: glycolysis, the Krebs cycle (also known as the Citric acid cycle), and oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] In Oxidative phosphorylation, ATP is synthesized from ADP and a phosphate using ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] ATP synthase is powered by a proton-motive force created by using the energy generated from the electron transport chain.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] A hydrogen ion (H+) has a positive charge and if separated by a cellular membrane, it creates a difference in charge between the inside and outside of the membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Oxidative phosphorylation occurs in the mitochondria of eukaryotes.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Aerobic respiration needs O2 because it acts as the terminal electron acceptor in prokaryotes' electron transport chain.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-organism] Molecular Oxygen is reduced to water in this process.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] It is the aerobic counterpart of bacterial vaginosis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The lack of acknowledgement of the difference between the two conditions might have led to inaccurate conclusions in several studies in the past.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The entity that has been described as "desquamative inflammatory vaginitis" probably corresponds to the more severe forms of aerobic vaginitis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Women with aerobic vaginitis usually have a thinned reddish vaginal mucosa, sometimes with extensive erosions or ulcerations and abundant yellowish discharge (without the fishy amine odour, typical of bacterial vaginosis).
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Discharge is not always typical, and can range from sticky green/yellow to excessive and watery.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The pH can be high, but can also be within normal range, making it an unreliable indicator for infection.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Symptoms can include burning, stinging and dyspareunia.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Symptoms typically improve during menstruation, and flare afterwards.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The symptoms can last for long periods, sometimes even years.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Typically, patients have been treated several times with antimycotic and antibiotic drugs without relief.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] In asymptomatic cases, there is microscopic evidence but no symptoms.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The prevalence of asymptomatic cases is unknown.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The diagnosis is based on microscopic criteria.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Ideally, phase-contrast microscopy is used with a magnification of 400x (high-power field) or by Gram stain.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The "AV score" is calculated according to what is described in the table.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] pH measurement alone is not enough for the diagnosis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Treatment is not always easy and aims at correcting the three key changes encountered in aerobic vaginitis: the presence of atrophy, inflammation and abnormal flora.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The treatment can include topical steroids to diminish the inflammation and topical estrogen to reduce the atrophy.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The use and choice of antibiotics to diminish the load/proportion of aerobic bacteria is still a matter of debate.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] The use of local antibiotics, preferably local non-absorbed and broad-spectrum, covering enteric gram-positive and gram-negative aerobes, like kanamycin, can be an option.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] In some cases, systemic antibiotics can be helpful, such as Amoxicillin/clavulanic acidor moxifloxacin.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Vaginal rinsing with povidone iodine can provide rapid relief of symptoms but does not provide long-term reduction of bacterial loads.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Dequalinium chloride can also be an option for treatment.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] More recently, evidence of natural remedies such as topical herbal medicine, combined with biofilm disrupters such as EDTA, has proven successful in cases of aerobic vaginitis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Biofilms prove yet another hurdle when treating aerobic vaginitis, especially in chronic cases.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Topical biofilm disrupters, such as EDTA, can be useful, with systemic biofilm disrupters such as Serralase also having evidence of helping to disrupt bacterial biofilms, and helping to treat this condition.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] About 5 to 10% of women are affected by aerobic vaginitis.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] Reports in pregnant women point to a prevalence of 8.3–10.8%.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerobic-vaginitis] When considering symptomatic women, the prevalence of AV can be as high as 23%.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerotolerant] There are three categories of anaerobes.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerotolerant] Where obligate aerobes require oxygen to grow, obligate anaerobes are damaged by oxygen, aerotolerant organisms cannot use oxygen but tolerate its presence, and facultative anaerobes use oxygen if it is present but can grow without it.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerotolerant] Most aerotolerant anaerobes have superoxide dismutase and (non-catalase) peroxidase but do not have catalase.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerotolerant] More specifically, they may use a NADH oxidase/NADH peroxidase (NOX/NPR) system or a glutathione peroxidase system.
[src:aerobic-organism/aerotolerant] An example of an aerotolerant anaerobe is *Cutibacterium acnes*.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] ATP synthase lies across a cellular membrane and forms an aperture that protons can cross from areas of high concentration to areas of low concentration, imparting energy for the synthesis of ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This electrochemical gradient is generated by the electron transport chain and allows cells to store energy in ATP for later use.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In prokaryotic cells ATP synthase lies across the plasma membrane, while in eukaryotic cells it lies across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Organisms capable of photosynthesis also have ATP synthase across the thylakoid membrane, which in plants is located in the chloroplast and in cyanobacteria is located in the cytoplasm.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] ATP synthase is present in all organisms studied.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Eukaryotic ATP synthases are F-ATPases (which usually work as ATP synthases instead of ATPases in cellular environments) and running "in reverse" for an ATPase (ATPases catalyze the decomposition of ATP into ADP and a free phosphate ion).
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This article deals mainly with this type.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] An F-ATPase consists of two main subunits, FO and F1, which has a rotational motor mechanism allowing for ATP production.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F1 fraction derives its name from the term "Fraction 1" and FO (written as a subscript letter "o", not "zero") derives its name from being the binding fraction for oligomycin, a type of naturally derived antibiotic that is able to inhibit the FO unit of ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] These functional regions consist of different protein subunits — refer to tables.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This enzyme is used in synthesis of ATP through aerobic respiration.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Located within the thylakoid membrane and the inner mitochondrial membrane, ATP synthase consists of two regions FO and F1.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] FO causes rotation of F1 and is made of c-ring and subunits a, two b, F6.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] F1 has a water-soluble part that can hydrolyze ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] FO on the other hand has mainly hydrophobic regions.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] FO F1 creates a pathway for protons movement across the membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F1 portion of ATP synthase is hydrophilic and responsible for hydrolyzing ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F1 unit protrudes into the cytoplasm (matrix and stroma in mitochondria and chloroplasts respectively).
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Subunits α and β make a hexamer with 6 binding sites.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Three of them are catalytically inactive and they bind ADP.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Three other subunits catalyze the ATP synthesis.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The other F1 subunits γ, δ, and ε are a part of a rotational motor mechanism (rotor/axle).
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The γ subunit allows β to go through conformational changes (i.e., closed, half open, and open states) that allow for ATP to be bound and released once synthesized.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F1 particle is large and can be seen in the transmission electron microscope by negative staining.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] These are particles of 9 nm diameter that pepper the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] FO is a water insoluble protein with eight subunits and a transmembrane ring.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The FO region of ATP synthase is a proton pore that is embedded in the mitochondrial membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] It consists of three main subunits, a, b, and c.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Six c subunits make up the rotor ring, and subunit b makes up a stalk connecting to F1 OSCP that prevents the αβ hexamer from rotating.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Humans have six additional subunits, d, e, f, g, F6, and 8 (or A6L).
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This part of the enzyme is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and couples proton translocation to the rotation that causes ATP synthesis in the F1 region.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In eukaryotes, mitochondrial FO forms membrane-bending dimers.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] These dimers self-arrange into long rows at the end of the cristae, possibly the first step of cristae formation.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] An atomic model for the dimeric yeast FO region was determined by cryo-EM at an overall resolution of 3.6 Å.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In the 1960s through the 1970s, Paul Boyer, a UCLA Professor, developed the binding change, or flip-flop, mechanism theory, which postulated that ATP synthesis is dependent on a conformational change in ATP synthase generated by rotation of the gamma subunit.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Walker, then at the MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology in Cambridge, crystallized the F1 catalytic-domain of ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The structure, at the time the largest asymmetric protein structure known, indicated that Boyer's rotary-catalysis model was, in essence, correct.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] For elucidating this, Boyer and Walker shared half of the 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The crystal structure of the F1 showed alternating alpha and beta subunits (3 of each), arranged like segments of an orange around a rotating asymmetrical gamma subunit.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] A portion of the FO (the ring of c-subunits) rotates as the protons pass through the membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The c-ring is tightly attached to the asymmetric central stalk (consisting primarily of the gamma subunit), causing it to rotate within the alpha3beta3 of F1 causing the 3 catalytic nucleotide binding sites to go through a series of conformational changes that lead to ATP synthesis.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The major F1 subunits are prevented from rotating in sympathy with the central stalk rotor by a peripheral stalk that joins the alpha3beta3 to the non-rotating portion of FO.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The structure of the intact ATP synthase is currently known at low-resolution from electron cryo-microscopy (cryo-EM) studies of the complex.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The cryo-EM model of ATP synthase suggests that the peripheral stalk is a flexible structure that wraps around the complex as it joins F1 to FO.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Under the right conditions, the enzyme reaction can also be carried out in reverse, with ATP hydrolysis driving proton pumping across the membrane.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The binding change mechanism involves the active site of a β subunit's cycling between three states.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In the "loose" state, ADP and phosphate enter the active site; in the adjacent diagram, this is shown in pink.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The enzyme then undergoes a change in shape and forces these molecules together, with the active site in the resulting "tight" state (shown in red) binding the newly produced ATP molecule with very high affinity.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Finally, the active site cycles back to the open state (orange), releasing ATP and binding more ADP and phosphate, ready for the next cycle of ATP production.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Like other enzymes, the activity of F1FO ATP synthase is reversible.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Large-enough quantities of ATP cause it to create a transmembrane proton gradient, this is used by fermenting bacteria that do not have an electron transport chain, but rather hydrolyze ATP to make a proton gradient, which they use to drive flagella and the transport of nutrients into the cell.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In respiring bacteria under physiological conditions, ATP synthase, in general, runs in the opposite direction, creating ATP while using the proton motive force created by the electron transport chain as a source of energy.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The overall process of creating energy in this fashion is termed oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The same process takes place in the mitochondria, where ATP synthase is located in the inner mitochondrial membrane and the F1-part projects into the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] By pumping proton cations into the matrix, the ATP-synthase converts ADP into ATP.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The evolution of ATP synthase is thought to have been modular whereby two functionally independent subunits became associated and gained new functionality.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This association appears to have occurred early in evolutionary history, because essentially the same structure and activity of ATP synthase enzymes are present in all kingdoms of life.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F-ATP synthase displays high functional and mechanistic similarity to the V-ATPase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] However, whereas the F-ATP synthase generates ATP by utilising a proton gradient, the V-ATPase generates a proton gradient at the expense of ATP, generating pH values of as low as 1.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The F1 region also shows significant similarity to hexameric DNA helicases (especially the Rho factor), and the entire enzyme region shows some similarity to H+ -powered T3SS or flagellar motor complexes.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The α3β3 hexamer of the F1 region shows significant structural similarity to hexameric DNA helicases; both form a ring with 3-fold rotational symmetry with a central pore.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The H+ motor of the FO particle shows great functional similarity to the H+ motors that drive flagella.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Both feature a ring of many small alpha-helical proteins that rotate relative to nearby stationary proteins, using a H+ potential gradient as an energy source.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This link is tenuous, however, as the overall structure of flagellar motors is far more complex than that of the FO particle and the ring with about 30 rotating proteins is far larger than the 10, 11, or 14 helical proteins in the FO complex.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] More recent structural data do however show that the ring and the stalk are structurally similar to the F1 particle.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The modular evolution theory for the origin of ATP synthase suggests that two subunits with independent function, a DNA helicase with ATPase activity and a H+ motor, were able to bind, and the rotation of the motor drove the ATPase activity of the helicase in reverse.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This complex then evolved greater efficiency and eventually developed into today's intricate ATP synthases.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Alternatively, the DNA helicase/H+ motor complex may have had H+ pump activity with the ATPase activity of the helicase driving the H+ motor in reverse.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This may have evolved to carry out the reverse reaction and act as an ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] A variety of natural and synthetic inhibitors of ATP synthase have been discovered.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] These have been used to probe the structure and mechanism of ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] There are several classes of ATP synthase inhibitors, including peptide inhibitors, polyphenolic phytochemicals, polyketides, organotin compounds, polyenic α-pyrone derivatives, cationic inhibitors, substrate analogs, amino acid modifiers, and other miscellaneous chemicals.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Some of the most commonly used ATP synthase inhibitors are oligomycin and DCCD.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Bacterial F-ATPases can occasionally operate in reverse, turning them into an ATPase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Some bacteria have no F-ATPase, using an A/V-type ATPase bidirectionally.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Yeast ATP synthase is one of the best-studied eukaryotic ATP synthases; and five F1, eight FO subunits, and seven associated proteins have been identified.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Most of these proteins have homologues in other eukaryotes.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] In plants, ATP synthase is also present in chloroplasts (CF1FO-ATP synthase).
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The enzyme is integrated into thylakoid membrane; the CF1-part sticks into stroma, where dark reactions of photosynthesis (also called the light-independent reactions or the Calvin cycle) and ATP synthesis take place.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The overall structure and the catalytic mechanism of the chloroplast ATP synthase are almost the same as those of the bacterial enzyme.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] However, in chloroplasts, the proton motive force is generated not by respiratory electron transport chain but by primary photosynthetic proteins.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The synthase has a 40-aa insert in the gamma-subunit to inhibit wasteful activity when dark.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The ATP synthase isolated from bovine (*Bos taurus*) heart mitochondria is, in terms of biochemistry and structure, the best-characterized ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Beef heart is used as a source for the enzyme because of the high concentration of mitochondria in cardiac muscle.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Their genes have close homology to human ATP synthases.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Eukaryotes belonging to some divergent lineages have very special organizations of the ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] A euglenozoa ATP synthase forms a dimer with a boomerang-shaped F1 head like other mitochondrial ATP synthases, but the FO subcomplex has many unique subunits.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] The inhibitory IF1 also binds differently, in a way shared with trypanosomatida.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Apicomplexans, such as *Plasmodium*, utilise a hexameric ATP synthase organisation existing as a trimer of ATP synthase dimers.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] These hexameric assemblies arrange into pentagonal pyramids, which induce a unique bulbous cristae membrane morphology.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] This organisation is underpinned by both apicomplexan-specific subunits and cardiolipins.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Archaea do not generally have an F-ATPase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Instead, they synthesize ATP using the A-ATPase/synthase, a rotary machine structurally similar to the V-ATPase but mainly functioning as an ATP synthase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] Like the bacteria F-ATPase, it is believed to also function as an ATPase.
[src:aerobic-organism/atp-synthase] F-ATPase gene linkage and gene order are widely conserved across ancient prokaryote lineages, implying that this system already existed at a date before the last universal common ancestor, the LUCA.
